title: For Sale/Trade:  37MM "Reloading" Projectiles
postcontent:
these 37MM resin cast fin stabilized projectiles comes in three pieces.  the nose cone, the screw on fin section, and the pushing cup. This projectile can be fused or un-fused. The nose cone can be loaded with chalk or paint for practice/marker rounds. or you can also load them with flare, smoke, or firework burst compounds. These fin-stabilized, empty projectiles are sized to fit most 37mm 4.5" inch Aluminum casings/hulls. unlike other projectile designs. the longer three flute fin design makes this projectile fly straighter and farther then most short four fin projectiles.


the pushing cup is a 37mm reloading component used to help non-flat bottom projectiles reach their maximum distance. This 37mm reloading component is designed to be used with this projectile in 37mm aluminum casings/hulls.

check federal, state, and local laws on regulations before constructing any 37mm cartridges.  

Buyer assumes all risk involved in loading, reloading, constructing, and using 37mm cartridges

title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer P226
postcontent:
Sig Sauer P226 in 40 cal. It is a magnificent handgun and fires flawlessly

The (very bright) sights are TruGlo Night sights. 
The grips are Hogue G10 Piranhas
Blackhawk Serpa Holster
Three Mecgar magazines

As you can see in the pics, there is some holster wear on the barrel.

I'm selling (or trading) it for two reasons: I have found that I am a Glock guy. 
I have owned a number of handguns.....and I shoot regularly. And I currently have several Glocks. So I bought the Sig in hopes that I could get into something other than a Glock. But this Sig, quite honestly, is too darn big for my hand. And that's the second reason......this P226 is very accurate and has probably a 4-4.5 trigger......no creep.....nice and crisp. But the overall pistol is just too large and heavy overall for me as I'm a small old guy (that's why I carry a weapon:). So the Glock suits me best.

So, the pistol on its own (with a couple of mags) is worth about $700....on the low side. The Hogue Piranhas were just over $100. New Night sights....$100. Serpa Holster...$50. So a total of $950.  But I don't have the original box nor manual (you can run off the manual online).....so take off $50.  Go out and buy a new stock p226 and it will cost over $1000....plus tax. So I will sell mine for $850 and you will have a fabulous pistol. But you'd better be larger guy to handle it well.

Email me for more pics or info.

I will also consider trades. I like All Glocks in 40 cal. Or the new Glock 380. I also would consider an AR 10, quality optics.

title: For Sale:  Hazen Knives Sergeant Major, Handmade with 154CM Steel
location: Charlotte, 4724 Old Pineville Rd., Charlotte, North Carolina
postcontent: Locally made in Monroe, NC. SERGEANT MAJOR (Legion of Honor Series) with Micarta Handle & SheathOne of the most popular Hazen Knife models, the Sergeant Major is a double edged combat fighter that offers extreme comfort and grip control during extended use.Standard Knife SpecificationsOverall length - 11 1/2"Blade material - 154 CM (3/16") stainless steelBlade hardened to 57-59 RCBlade finish - matteBlade length - 6 3/16"Blade width - 1 1/4"Handle - 4 1/2"Handle material - black canvas MicartaHandle bolts - stainless steelGuard - stainless steel - matteSheath - black LeatherApprox. Weight - 9.8 oz.In August of 1976, Mark Hazen started his career as a custom knife maker. At that time, he could not afford to purchase a custom knife, so he decided to make his own. That's when it all began. Initially, Mark made knives for his friends and eventually, his creative talent was sought after by customers throughout the USA. After 30 years as a renowned knife maker, Mark decided to retire in 2007. On September 23, 2013, he received a call from Colonel Jack Tobin, president of The Special Forces Association at Fort Bragg, NC. While at an estate auction preview, Colonel Tobin saw a knife which he felt would be perfect for Special Forces active duty personnel, as well as the members of the association. Mark came out of retirement and began his journey by making a knife in honor of his fallen friend, MSG Robert Horrigan, a Special Forces Operator stationed at Fort Bragg, NC.Mark Hazen, who mastered the art of knife making over the past 30 years, is reintroducing classic old world craftsmanship in new and innovative designs. Each knife is hand made without the use of jigs. The blade and edge geometry has been engineered into each model to ensure optimum performance for its intended use. The ergonomically designed handles are specifically contoured to give a comfortable and confident grip. Each Hazen knife is uniquely crafted and well suited for all military and law enforcement personnel, sportsmen and the discriminating collector.All the knives produced at Hazen Knives go through a 3-phase testing process to ensure that each knife meets uncompromising quality standards. Each batch of steel is tested since all are not exactly the same. One knife is made from each new batch and is rigorously tested by chopping through a 2X4 piece of lumber and cleanly slicing through a piece of 20 lb. paper. If the hardness and edge retention meet the standards of phase one, the cutting test, then the testing continues to phase two, the comfort test and phase three, the fit and finish test.Come check this knife out in person at The Arms Room in Charlotte. Give me a call @ 980-237-eight9eight1 if you have any questions. Shipping can be arranged for $10.
